[00:00.00]Lesson 26 The past life of the earth\n地球上的昔日生命\n
[00:07.70]First listen and then answer the following question.\n听录音,然后回答以下问题.\n
[00:11.56]What is the main condition for the preservation of the remains of any living creature?\n生物的尸体被保存下来的主要条件是什么?\n
[00:18.03]It is animals and plants which lived in or near water\n只有生活在水中或水边的动植物\n
[00:24.64]whose remains are most likely to be preserved,\n其尸体最有可能被保存下来,\n
[00:27.55]for one of the necessary conditions of preservation is quick burial,\n因保存的必要条件之一是迅速掩埋,\n
[00:32.53]and it is only in the seas and rivers, and sometimes lakes,\n所以只有在海洋和江河里有时在湖泊里,\n
[00:36.92]where mud and silt have been continuously deposited,\n这些泥沙不停淤积的地方\n
[00:40.33]that bodies and the like can be rapidly covered over and preserved.\n尸体之类的东西才能被迅速地覆盖而保存下来.\n
[00:45.18]But even in the most favourable circumstances\n即使是在最有利的环境中,\n
[00:49.12]only a small fraction of the creatures that die are preserved in this way\n死去的生物中也只有一小部分能被这样保存下来,\n
[00:53.79]before decay sets in or,even more likely, before scavengers eat them.\n在开始腐烂前,或更可能在被食腐动物吃掉之前,被这样保存下来.\n
[00:59.16]After all,all living creatures live by feeding on something else,\n因为一切生物都是靠吃别的东西来活命的,\n
[01:04.87]whether it be plant or animal,dead or alive,\n不管这种东西是植物还是动物,死的还是活的,\n
[01:08.74]and it is only by chance that such a fate is avoided.\n因此,生物偶尔才能避免被吃掉的命运.\n
[01:12.73]The remains of plants and animals that lived on land are much more rarely preserved,\n曾在陆地上生活过的动植物的遗体被保存下来的更为罕见,\n
[01:18.83]for there is seldom anything to cover them over.\n因为陆地上几乎没有什么东西覆盖它们.\n
[01:22.17]When you think of the innumerable birds that one sees flying about,\n你可以想象出天上有看得见的飞来飞去、数不清的鸟,\n
[01:27.30]not to mention the equally numerous small animals like field mice and voles\n地上有无数的老鼠和田鼠之类\n
[01:32.74]which you do not see,\n这些不显眼的小动物,\n
[01:34.20]it is very rarely that one comes across a dead body,except,of course,on the roads.\n但是,除非在路上,很少有人遇到这些动物的尸体,\n
[01:40.90]They decompose and are quickly destroyed by the weather or eaten by some other creature.\n因为它们腐败之后很快就被风化掉,或被别的动物吃掉了.\n
[01:48.09]It is almost always due to some very special circumstances\n几乎总是由于某些特殊的条件,\n
[01:53.04]that traces of land animals survive,\n陆地动物的遗体才被保存下来,\n
[01:55.73]as by falling into inaccessible caves,or into an ice crevasse,\n如掉进难以到达的洞穴,或冰窟中,aa\n
[02:02.19]like the Siberian mammoths,\n像西伯利亚长毛象那样,\n
[02:04.83]when the whole animal is sometimes preserved,as in a refrigerator.\n有时整个动物像被放在冰箱里一样被保存下来.\n
[02:09.71]This is what happened to the famous Beresovka mammoth\n著名的别林索夫卡长毛象就是这样aa\n
